sec.p:
Procedures for sampling and analyzing cortisol were the same as reported in Bohle et al.52 In short, all sampling was performed over two consecutive days, 4 times a day for each timepoint (T1-4). Samples were gathered using a saliva collection device (Sarstedt Nümbrecht, Germany) that consisted of a cotton swab and a sampling vessel. The samples were analyzed by Department of Medical Biochemistry, Møre, and Romsdal Hospital Trust. Cortisol levels were measured using an immunochemical assay on a Roche Cobas 8000 e801 automated analyzer (Roche Diagnostics, Oslo, Norway). To examine different aspects of HPA axis functioning, the daytime cortisol slope (DCS) and AUC were calculated. DCSs were quantified by calculating the difference between morning and afternoon samples divided by the total time between the two samples.78 The area under the curve with respect to the ground (AUCG) was calculated according to the method described by Pruessner et al.79 The AUCG is the total AUC of all measurements for each time point based on the mean time of day for each sample time (ST). The formula for AUCG is summarized as: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
